Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in the Netherlands. The Dutch authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
Travel restrictions
For information on how to return to the UK from the Netherlands, see Return to the UK.
Local measures
On 23 March, the Dutch government announced additional measures in response to the COVID-19 outbreak, including a ban on all gatherings with limited exemptions until 1 June. Full details of these measures can be found on the Dutch government website (in English). These measures are in addition to current measures (in English) which were introduced on 15 March.
Anyone experiencing any symptoms linked to coronavirus (COVID-19) (specifically a cough, cold, sore throat or fever) must remain at home until the symptoms have cleared. People are advised to stay a recommended distance of 1.5m from each other in public. All bars, caf√©s and restaurants are closed, although supermarkets remain open. Public places such as museums, concert venues, theatres and sports clubs are closed and sports events are cancelled. Medically vulnerable people and older people should avoid public transport.
These measures will apply until at least 6 April. You can find further information on the latest measures from the Dutch National Institute for Public Health (RIVM) and from the Dutch government.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in The Netherlands on the TravelHealthPro country page.
